					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: center;font-size: 75%">
					## 2. A Direct Measure of Inefficiency within Couples

					(Joint work with O. Bargain, D. Echevin & N. Moreau)
					</section>
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: center;font-size: 75%">
					How does cohabiting couples allocate their children between their two tax-units?
					</section>
										
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: center;font-size: 75%">
					### Context:
					- Cohabitants with children constitute two fiscal-unit
					- Children can be allocated between the two tax returns
					- There exists an optimal allocation in order to minimize the tax
					</section>
					<section>
							<aside class="notes">
									Exemple: père 17 968, mère 41 222
									Why would cohabitants do not choose the best allocation ?

							</aside>
						<iframe class="stretch"   src="./images/cohabitants-heatmap.html"></iframe>
					</section>
					
					<!-- <section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					## Analys
					Données: EDP
					1. Parmi 2 millions de foyers fiscaux en 2013, sélectionn 193 000 couples de cohabitants, dont 52 000 ont tous les enfants qui sont "biologiques" en 2013.
					2. Calcul de l'impôt des deux foyers fiscaux de chaque ménage en fonction de l'allocation des enfants.
					</section> -->
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					## Analysis
					Data: *Échantillong Démographique Permanent* (EDP)
					1. From 2 million fiscal households in 2013, I select 193 000 cohabiting couples, from which 52 000 has all their children identified as biological children in the civil registry.
					2. Compute the income tax for each of the two fiscal unit in each household based on children allocation.					</section>
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: center;font-size: 85%">
					25% of the households do not optimize their disposable income by not choosing the optimal allocation.  


					
					8% for households that do not optimize their disposable income up to 1% of their pre-tax income.


					</section>
					<!-- <section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					## Explications:
					</section>
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					Dynamique:  
					Optimisation en 2013 et en 2014 $\implies$
					Nous observons que l'inertie est un déterminant très fort de l'optimisation.
					</section> -->


					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: center;font-size: 75%">
					# Explanations:  
					I. The Dynamic  
					II. Cooperation
					</section>
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					## The Dynamic:  
					We observe that inertia is a very strong determinant of optimization.  
					Indeed households rarely change their allocation weather they should or not change their optimal allocation.
					</section>



					<!-- <section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					Coopération:  
					Multinomial Logit:  
					Les couples qui n'optimisent pas pour de larges valeurs du revenu imposable ont plus tendance à se séparer une fois que nous avont controlé pour un ensemble de covariables.

					À l'inverse, les couples qui optimisent ont une plus grande chance de se marier ou de se pacser.
					</section> -->
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					## Cooperation:  
					Multinomial Logit:  
					Couples that do not optimize for large values of their taxable income, are more likely to separate the year after, once controlled for a large set of covariates.  

					Conversely, couples that do optimize are more likely to mary or enter in a civil union.
					</section>

					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					![](./images/MNL_cooperation.png)

					</section>
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
					This suggest that non-cooperation is one of the derterminants of the non respect of efficiency inside households.
					<!-- Ceci suggère que la non-coopération est un des déterminants du non respect de l'efficacité au sein du ménage. -->
					</section>
					
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: center;font-size: 75%">
					# Next chapter.
					</section>


					</section>
				</section>
				<section>
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: Center;font-size: 75%">
					## 3. Rich households taxable income
					</section>
					<!-- <section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: Center;font-size: 75%">
					S'intéresse à comment les ménages Français ont réagi à l'abaissement du plafond du quotient familial vis à vis de leurs base taxable.
					</section>						 -->
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: Center;font-size: 75%">
					Question how rich French household reacted to the lowering of the maximum child tax break with respect to their taxable income?  
					</section>		
					<!-- <section>
						<h2>Contexte : </h2>
        <ol>
          <li>Le gain fiscal par enfant augmente avec le revenu.
          </li>
          <li>
            Cependant ce gain est limité par un plafond.
          </li>
          <li>
          Ce plafond a été abaissé de 2336 à 1500 euros en 2011 et2014. Ce montant est doublé à partir du troisième enfant et plus.
          </li>
        </ol>
					</section> -->
					<section>
						<h2>Context: </h2>
        <ol>
          <li>The French tax system works such that the child tax break is increasing with income.  
          </li>
          <li>
            However, the fiscal gain a household can derive from a child is bounded by a ceiling.  
          </li>
          <li>
					The ceiling per child has been lowered from 2336€ to 1500€ between 2011 and 2014. That per child ceiling is twice the baseline amount for the third child and over.
          </li>
        </ol>
					</section>

				<section>
						<h3> Households have been affected in three ways: </h3>
			<font size="6">
        <ol>
          <li>Households for which the fiscal advantage per child was lower than 1500 euros are unaffected.  
          </li>
          <li>
            Households for which the fiscal advantage per child was between 1500 euros and 2336 euros face a change in their marginal tax rate.  
          </li>
          <li>
					Households for which the fiscal advantage per child was over 2336 euros face a lump sum loss in disposable income of 836€ per child.
          </li>
        </ol>
			</font>
					</section>
					<!-- <section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
				On peut distinguer trois groupes de ménages:  	
				1. Les ménages pour qui le gain fiscal était inférieur à 1500 euros, et ne sont donc pas traités par la réforme.  
				2. Les ménages pour qui le gain fiscal était entre 1500 et 2336 euros. Ils font face à un changement de taux marginal.
				3. Les ménages pour qui le gain fiscal était supérieur à 2336 euros, et qui voient donc une réduction forfaitaire de leur révenu de 836 euros par demie-part. 
				</section> -->
					<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
									Implication:  
				As the fiscal advantage increases with income, there exists an income threshold at which a household will attain the ceiling. 
				<!-- L'avantage fiscal augmantant avec le revenu, il existe un seuil de revenu auquel les ménages vont atteindre le plafond du quotient familial:   -->

|# of children						|2011|	2013|
|------------|----------|----------|--------|--------|
|1	|63,083	|58,380
|2	|73,539	|63,396
|3	|94,343 |73,844
|4	|115,142	|84,095
|5	|135,922	|94,508
|6	|150,684	|104,691
					
					</section>
				
				<section>
					<iframe class="stretch" src="./images/bokeh_graph.html">
				  </iframe>
				</section>

		<section style = "text-align: left; font-size:71%;">
			<h3>A triple difference estimation :</h3>
			      <p>$$\begin{align*}
\Delta y_i &= \beta_0 + \sum_{i=1}^{6} {\beta_i \text{Children}_i} + \sum_{j=1}^{6} {{}_{b}\delta_i \text{Between}_i}  + \sum_{i=1}^{6} {{}_{o}\delta_i \text{Over}_j} \\
    &+ \sum_{i=1}^6 {{}_{b}\gamma_{i} \text{Children}_i \times \text{Between}_i} \\
    &+ \sum_{i=1}^6 {{}_{o}\gamma_{i} \text{Children}_i \times \text{Over}_i} \\
    & + \epsilon_i
\end{align*}$$ </p>
		</section>
		<section>
		<img class="stretch" data-src="./images/Triple_diff_result_simple.png">
		</section>
		<section>
		<h3>Income dynamic</h3>
		<img class="stretch" data-src="./images/income_dynamics.png">
		</section>
		<section  data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
		The common trend assumption is not respected.  
		Once comensated for  the initial before the reform trend, the results are not holding anymore.
		</section>
			</section>

	<section>
		<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: center;font-size: 75%">
		# Conclusion
		</section>
		<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
		 The first chapter looks at a subject that has not been much studied. It gives hindsight about the impact of the frequency of the tax, and provides a methodology to assess quantitatively the impact that a change in the frequency of the tax. 
		</section>
		<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
		 The second chapter shows that households does not always respect efficiency.
		</section>
		<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
		The third chapters tries to assess the behavioral reactions associated with a tax reform. It does so by relying on a "new" methodology that was supposed to solve many existing caveats in the litterature. This methology also tries to disentengle the income effect and the substitution effect.  

		However, the common trend assumptions is not respected, and once corrected for the trend before the reform, the results tend to show a null effect of the reform.
		</section>
		<section data-markdown  style =  "text-align: left;font-size: 75%">
		## Reproducibility, and the the scientific method 
		- All the code to produce the thesis is available on [https://github.com/adrienpacifico/Thesis_Taxation_2019](https://github.com/adrienpacifico/Thesis_Taxation_2019)
		</section>

		</section>
	</section>

